assets/faces/lm2/haha.gif\" class=\"hkgmoji\" /><img src=\"/assets/faces/lm2/haha.gif\" class=\"hkgmoji\" /><img src=\"/assets/faces/lm2/haha.gif\" class=\"hkgmoji\" /><img src=\"/assets/faces/lm2/haha.gif\" class=\"hkgmoji\" /><br />\n=====================================<br />\n&bull;The song, titled Trade War, has taken off on social media platform WeChat<br />\n&bull;'If the perpetrator wants to fight, we will beat him out of his wits,' the lyrics read<br />\n&bull;China is rallying public support around its position in trade dispute with US  <br />\n&bull;Films about the Korean War have also made reappearances during prime-time<br />\n<br />\n<img src=\"https://i.dailymail.co.uk/1s/2019/05/20/17/13725354-7050305-_If_the_perpetrator_wants_to_fight_we_will_beat_him_out_of_his_w-a-103_1558368837229.jpg\" data-thumbnail-src=\"https://i.lih.kg/thumbnail?u=https%3A%2F%2Fi.dailymail.co.uk%2F1s%2F2019%2F05%2F20%2F17%2F13725354-7050305-_If_the_perpetrator_wants_to_fight_we_will_beat_him_out_of_his_w-a-103_1558368837229.jpg&h=46c07c8e&s={SIZE}\" /><br />\n 'If the perpetrator wants to fight, we will beat him out of his wits,' the lyrics of the privately produced song titled Trade War read. It has gathered more than 3.2 million views on WeChat<br />\n<br />\n<img src=\"https://i.dailymail.co.uk/1s/2019/05/20/17/13725358-7050305-image-a-104_1558368875928.jpg\" data-thumbnail-src=\"https://i.lih.kg/thumbnail?u=https%3A%2F%2Fi.dailymail.co.uk%2F1s%2F2019%2F05%2F20%2F17%2F13725358-7050305-image-a-104_1558368875928.jpg&h=83e7a519&s={SIZE}\" /><br />\n The song, released by producer and lyricist Zhao Liangtian, is set to the tun of an anti-Japanese anthem from the 1960s film Tunnel War - in which a Chinese town defends itself from invasion. Above, the lyrics read 'we will beat him out of his wits'<br />\n<br />\n<img src=\"https://i.dailymail.co.uk/1s/2019/05/20/17/13725302-7050305-State_broadcaster_CCTV_s_movie_channel_changed_its_prime_time_sc-a-112_1558369038277.jpg\" data-thumbnail-src=\"https://i.lih.kg/thumbnail?u=https%3A%2F%2Fi.dailymail.co.uk%2F1s%2F2019%2F05%2F20%2F17%2F13725302-7050305-State_broadcaster_CCTV_s_movie_channel_changed_its_prime_time_sc-a-112_1558369038277.jpg&h=7378519f&s={SIZE}\" /><br />\n State broadcaster CCTV's movie channel changed its prime-time schedule from live-streaming the red carpet of Asian Movie Week to a number of post-war film classics, including Battle on Shangganling Mountain (1954)<br />\n<br />\n<img src=\"https://i.dailymail.co.uk/1s/2019/05/20/17/13725298-7050305-Heroic_Sons_and_Daughters_1964_was_aired_on_May_16_during_prime_-a-113_1558369041016.jpg\" data-thumbnail-src=\"https://i.lih.kg/thumbnail?u=https%3A%2F%2Fi.dailymail.co.uk%2F1s%2F2019%2F05%2F20%2F17%2F13725298-7050305-Heroic_Sons_and_Daughters_1964_was_aired_on_May_16_during_prime_-a-113_1558369041016.jpg&h=894f59b6&s={SIZE}\" /><br />\n Heroic Sons and Daughters (1964) was aired on May 16 during prime-time on CCTV<br />\n<br />\n<img src=\"https://i.dailymail.co.uk/1s/2019/05/20/17/13725304-7050305-Surprise_Attack_1960_was_aired_on_Saturday_on_CCTV_during_prime_-a-115_1558369276412.jpg\" data-thumbnail-src=\"https://i.lih.kg/thumbnail?u=https%3A%2F%2Fi.dailymail.co.uk%2F1s%2F2019%2F05%2F20%2F17%2F13725304-7050305-Surprise_Attack_1960_was_aired_on_Saturday_on_CCTV_during_prime_-a-115_1558369276412.jpg&h=d812ebf8&s={SIZE}\" /><br />\n Surprise Attack (1960) was aired on Saturday on CCTV during prime-time. The film is set during the Korean War, otherwise known in China as the War to Resist American Aggression and Aid Korea<br />\n<br />\n<img src=\"https://i.dailymail.co.uk/1s/2019/05/15/11/13442192-7031507-President_Donald_Trump_right_expanded_his_tariff_regime_to_inclu-a-27_1557915324048.jpg\" data-thumbnail-src=\"https://i.lih.kg/thumbnail?u=https%3A%2F%2Fi.dailymail.co.uk%2F1s%2F2019%2F05%2F15%2F11%2F13442192-7031507-President_Donald_Trump_right_expanded_his_tariff_regime_to_inclu-a-27_1557915324048.jpg&h=0872ce4a&s={SIZE}\" /><br />\n President Donald Trump (right) expanded his tariff regime to include practically everything China exports to the US; Chinese President Xi Jinping (left) retaliated last Monday but said his own tariffs won't go into effect until June. The pair are pictured in November 2017<br />\n<br />\n<img src=\"https://i.dailymail.co.uk/1s/2019/05/20/13/13709978-7048817-image-a-13_1558355674051.jpg\" data-thumbnail-src=\"https://i.lih.kg/thumbnail?u=https%3A%2F%2Fi.dailymail.co.uk%2F1s%2F2019%2F05%2F20%2F13%2F13709978-7048817-image-a-13_1558355674051.jpg&h=54422b54&s={SIZE}\" /><br />\n Chinese smartphone maker Huawei has been blocked by Google from receiving updates for the Android operating system during a trade war between Beijing and Washington<br />\n<br />\n<img src=\"https://i.dailymail.co.uk/1s/2019/05/15/11/13456644-7031507-China_announced_Monday_it_would_raise_tariffs_on_60_billion_in_U-a-28_1557915327171.jpg\" data-thumbnail-src=\"https://i.lih.kg/thumbnail?u=https%3A%2F%2Fi.dailymail.co.uk%2F1s%2F2019%2F05%2F15%2F11%2F13456644-7031507-China_announced_Monday_it_would_raise_tariffs_on_60_billion_in_U-a-28_1557915327171.jpg&h=993c25c3&s={SIZE}\" /><br />\n China announced last Monday it would raise tariffs on $60 billion in US exports by next month, responding in kind to President Donald Trump's decision last week to hike duties on hundreds of billions of dollars in Chinese merchandise<br />\n<br />\n<img src=\"https://i.dailymail.co.uk/1s/2019/05/15/11/13456646-7031507-A_Chinese_worker_adjusts_a_hydraulic_lift_at_a_factory_which_pro-a-29_1557915329199.jpg\" data-thumbnail-src=\"https://i.lih.kg/thumbnail?u=https%3A%2F%2Fi.dailymail.co.uk%2F1s%2F2019%2F05%2F15%2F11%2F13456646-7031507-A_Chinese_worker_adjusts_a_hydraulic_lift_at_a_factory_which_pro-a-29_1557915329199.jpg&h=b881dada&s={SIZE}\" /><br />\n A Chinese worker adjusts a hydraulic lift at a factory which produces construction machinery for export to many countries, including the US, in Jinan, in east China's Shandong province<br />\n<br />\n<a href=\"https://videos.dailymail.co.uk/video/mol/2019/05/20/3668938546966937224/1024x576_MP4_3668938546966937224.mp4\" data-sr-url=\"https://r.lihkg.com/link?u=https%3A%2F%2Fvideos.dailymail.co.uk%2Fvideo%2Fmol%2F2019%2F05%2F20%2F3668938546966937224%2F1024x576_MP4_3668938546966937224.mp4&d=Udlbz0MX%2FrD6%2BzJW%2FeuWbYtKjO%2FIGoH7AJS0Ocrd4mI%3D&h=d1f8c6aa\" target=\"_blank\">https://videos.dailymail.co.uk/video/mol/2019/05/20/3668938546966937224/1024x576_MP4_3668938546966937224.mp4</a><br />\n<br />\nsource:<a href=\"https://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-7050305/Patriotic-Chinese-web-users-using-anti-U-S-viral-song-support-Beijing-trade-war.html\" data-sr-url=\"https://r.lihkg.com/link?u=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.dailymail.co.uk%2Fnews%2Farticle-7050305%2FPatriotic-Chinese-web-users-using-anti-U-S-viral-song-support-Beijing-trade-war.html&d=Udlbz0MX%2FrD6%2BzJW%2FeuWbYtKjO%2FIGoH7AJS0Ocrd4mI%3D&h=34452282\" target=\"_blank\">https://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-7050305/Patriotic-Chinese-web-users-using-anti-U-S-viral-song-support-Beijing-trade-war.html</a>"},{"pid":"73bee4592320745a2db68b6d71cafbf6c40d5bf3","tid":1164064,"uid":123738,"like":0,"dislike":0,"score":0,"citedBy":0,"replyTime":"2019-05-21T00:30:17.000Z","msg":"支那又贏！<img src=\"/assets/faces/lm2/bye.gif\" class=\"hkgmoji\" />"},{"pid":"4d2228ac6db41a44bef041bd2dcc56f47813ef0a","tid":1164064,"uid":184679,"like":0,"dislike":0,"score":0,"citedBy":0,"replyTime":"2019-05-21T01:45:56.000Z","msg":"<img src=\"/assets/faces/normal/clown.gif\" class=\"hkgmoji\" />"},{"pid":"14c4abe8aa26f7741068cb2c0eefc154ef820fd2","tid":1164064,"uid":107927,"like":0,"dislike":0,"score":0,"citedBy":0,"replyTime":"2019-05-21T01:48:03.000Z","msg":"唔打就係契弟<br />\n打啦!"},{"pid":"52def9fc9e49aa167f903db897c6b0f59af8211e","tid":1164064,"uid":74908,"like":0,"dislike":0,"score":0,"citedBy":0,"replyTime":"2019-05-21T01:49:56.000Z","msg":"笑咗出聲<img src=\"/assets/faces/normal/sosad.gif\" class=\"hkgmoji\" /><img